      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Open Home Cadence and Scheduling Strategy for Brisbane Sellers
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        When you run inspections, how often, and which slots you choose all shape the campaign's momentum. Saturday mornings, twilight, midweek opens, private inspections, and how the rhythm should evolve from week one to week five.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most of the writing about open homes focuses on what to do on the day: declutter, ventilate, light a candle, leave the property to the agent. That advice is useful but it answers the wrong question. The strategic decision in the campaign is not what to do at the open. It is when to schedule the open, how often to run them, and which slot suits the property and its buyer pool. A well-presented home at the wrong time or with the wrong cadence underperforms a moderately presented home that meets its buyers when they are actually available to inspect.</p>

      <p>This article is for Brisbane sellers thinking through the timing and rhythm of the campaign. It covers the merits of Saturday morning slots, the role of twilight inspections, when midweek opens earn their place, how many inspections per week is the right number, when to switch from public opens to private inspections only, and how the cadence should change as the campaign moves from launch to active to negotiation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why scheduling matters as much as preparation</h2>
      <p>Buyer behaviour at inspections is shaped by competition. A buyer who walks into an open home with three other groups already inspecting reads the property differently from a buyer who walks into an empty open at the same property. The first buyer is calibrating against other interested parties; the second is calibrating against an empty room. The first scenario produces stronger offers; the second produces hesitation.</p>

      <p>The schedule's primary job is to consolidate qualified buyers into the same inspection window so they can see each other, feel the competitive pressure, and make decisions accordingly. A schedule that scatters buyers across too many slots dilutes that effect. A schedule that concentrates them effectively amplifies it.</p>

      <p>This is the lens through which every decision about cadence and timing should be made. The best slot is not the one that maximises foot traffic in a vacuum; it is the one that maximises competitive density at each inspection.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Saturday mornings: the default for good reason</h2>
      <p>The Saturday morning slot, typically running for thirty to forty-five minutes between 9:30am and 11:30am, has been the spine of Brisbane sale campaigns for years because of how it aligns with buyer behaviour. Most active buyers in the inner east plan their inspections around Saturday mornings. Couples make a list of properties to see, drive between them, and use the morning as a structured comparison exercise. Concentrating your open home in this window puts the property into that structured comparison alongside the homes the buyer is already planning to see.</p>

      <p>Within Saturday morning, the slot itself matters. The first slot of the morning (often 9am or 9:30am) catches the buyers who are starting their planned route and have the freshest energy. The middle slot (10am to 10:30am) catches the largest cross-section. The late slot (11am to 11:30am) catches buyers who are finishing their route and may be tired but also closer to a decision. The agent's choice within the morning often comes down to what the rest of the planned inspection list looks like across the suburb that weekend, and where the property sits geographically in a buyer's likely driving route.</p>

      <p>The default Saturday morning open should not be defaulted to without thought, but it should be the starting point and the burden should be on a specific reason to deviate.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Twilight inspections: when they earn their slot</h2>
      <p>Twilight inspections, typically 5pm to 6:30pm in the warmer months and 4:30pm to 6pm in winter, work for specific properties and specific reasons. They suit homes whose presentation is enhanced by evening light: city or river outlooks that read better at dusk, west-facing decks that catch the late sun, gardens or pools lit for evening use, and homes whose interior lighting design is part of the appeal. They also suit campaigns where the buyer pool includes professionals who cannot easily commit to weekend inspections and prefer a midweek evening slot.</p>

      <p>Twilights do not work for every property. Homes with an east-facing aspect that goes flat in the late afternoon, properties on noisy roads that are louder in the evening, and homes whose strongest light is morning sun all present worse at twilight than they do on a Saturday morning. Defaulting to a twilight inspection because it sounds glamorous is a mistake when the property's actual light favours the morning.</p>

      <p>The right use of twilight slots is selectively, for properties whose presentation genuinely benefits and where the buyer pool includes people who want the option. Pairing one twilight inspection with the standard Saturday open can sometimes work; replacing the Saturday open with twilight rarely does.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Midweek inspections: who they reach</h2>
      <p>Midweek inspections, typically running for thirty minutes during the late afternoon (around 5pm to 5:30pm) or sometimes during the day, reach a different audience than Saturday mornings. The buyer pool includes downsizers, retirees, work-from-home professionals, second-home buyers visiting Brisbane from interstate, and active investors who can inspect during the working week.</p>

      <p>Midweek opens are most useful as a complement to the weekend, not a replacement. Properties that consistently see strong midweek attendance often have a buyer pool with flexible schedules; properties where midweek attendance is thin do not. The agent's reading of attendance after the first one or two weeks should inform whether to keep, expand, or wind back the midweek slot.</p>

      <p>One specific midweek role is for buyers who attended the Saturday open and want a second look before making an offer. A scheduled midweek inspection gives those buyers a clean way to return without staging a separate private appointment, and the visible second viewing often signals seriousness to other buyers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How many opens per week is the right number</h2>
      <p>The default Brisbane cadence in the active campaign period is one Saturday open plus one midweek inspection per week. This pair gives most properties enough exposure without dispersing the buyer pool. Some campaigns add a second Saturday slot in the first week to capture the early demand spike; some properties suit only the Saturday open if midweek attendance is consistently thin.</p>

      <p>Running three or more scheduled inspections per week tends to spread foot traffic too thinly and reduces the competitive density at each open. Running fewer than one inspection per week in the active period risks losing the rhythm that buyers expect and missing the comparison-shopping window. Within those bounds, the right number is the one that produces strong attendance at each scheduled inspection, not the highest possible total attendance across all inspections.</p>

      <p>For a more detailed treatment of the first-week setup specifically, see <a href="/insights/launching-brisbane-property-campaign-first-open-home-first-week" style="color:#f5d07a;">launching a Brisbane property campaign and the first week's open homes</a>.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to switch from open homes to private inspections only</h2>
      <p>The switch from public open homes to private inspections is one of the more under-discussed strategic moves in a campaign. The right moment is usually after the qualified buyer pool has been identified and the remaining work is consolidating offers from a small number of serious buyers. Continuing weekly public opens past that point spreads the agent's time across casual lookers and dilutes the urgency for the buyers who matter.</p>

      <p>Specific signals that suggest the switch is appropriate include three to five identified qualified buyers, attendance at recent opens dominated by repeat visitors, agent feedback that few new buyers are being added to the pool, and active price conversations with one or more interested parties. In these circumstances, replacing the next public open with private inspections by appointment for the qualified buyers can accelerate the negotiation phase.</p>

      <p>Continuing public opens too long is a risk because each consecutive open without an offer subtly signals that the property is not finding its market, even when the truth is that the market has been found and is being worked through privately. The campaign's rhythm is part of the message; allowing it to drift sends a message you do not want to send.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the cadence should evolve from week one to week five</h2>
      <p>A typical four to five week Brisbane sale campaign has a recognisable cadence. Week one launches the campaign with the first Saturday open, often the largest attendance of the campaign as the cumulative demand from the pre-launch period arrives. The first week may include a Wednesday or Thursday midweek inspection to capture buyers who could not make Saturday.</p>

      <p>Weeks two and three are the active campaign period, usually running the standard Saturday plus midweek pattern. Attendance settles into a pattern that reflects the property's natural buyer pool. The agent gathers feedback after each inspection and reports back to the seller on price expectations, level of interest, and the qualified buyer pool emerging.</p>

      <p>Weeks four and five, in a typical campaign, transition into negotiation. Public opens may continue or may give way to private inspections by appointment for the qualified pool. Decisions about price guide adjustment, transition to auction, or extension of the campaign sit in this window. The cadence here is increasingly tactical rather than scheduled, responding to the specific buyers in play.</p>

      <p>For more on adjusting when the campaign is not landing, see <a href="/insights/no-offers-after-four-weeks-brisbane-sale-campaign-diagnose-reset" style="color:#f5d07a;">diagnosing and resetting a campaign with no offers after four weeks</a>.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Reading buyer feedback to adjust the cadence</h2>
      <p>The cadence should not be set once and run on autopilot. The agent's feedback after each open should drive small adjustments week to week. Strong attendance with serious buyers asking specific questions suggests the slot and rhythm are working. Strong attendance with low engagement suggests the property may be drawing the wrong audience and the slot may need to change. Thin attendance suggests the slot, the marketing, or the price guide may all need review.</p>

      <p>For Brisbane sellers, the practical step is a brief conversation with the agent after each Saturday open, covering attendance, the buyers' apparent qualification level, the questions asked, the comparable properties being mentioned, and any feedback on price. That conversation, repeated weekly, is the input to whether the next week's cadence stays the same, expands, or contracts. See <a href="/insights/managing-buyer-feedback-during-brisbane-sale-campaign-signal-noise" style="color:#f5d07a;">managing buyer feedback during a Brisbane sale campaign</a> for more on what to listen for.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A simple four-question checklist before each week</h2>
      <p>Before locking in the next week's schedule, the seller and agent should be able to answer: 1. What did last week's inspections tell us about the buyer pool? 2. Which slots are producing competitive density and which are scattering buyers? 3. Are we still adding new qualified buyers to the pool, or is the pool now identified and being worked privately? 4. Does the next week's schedule reflect the answers to the first three questions, or is it just a default carried forward? Asking these questions weekly keeps the cadence intentional rather than mechanical.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The bottom line</h2>
      <p>Open home cadence and scheduling is one of the highest-leverage decisions in a sale campaign and one of the least discussed. The right approach is to anchor on the Saturday morning open, add midweek and twilight slots only where they earn their place, keep the schedule rhythmic in the early weeks and tactical in the later weeks, and switch from public opens to private inspections when the qualified pool has been identified. Properties that get the cadence right run smoother, attract stronger buyers at each inspection, and reach negotiation in better shape than properties that simply repeat the same schedule for five weeks regardless of what the data shows.</p>

